------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1) Interface Changes:
    - Interface is collection of abstract methods.
    - The methods which does not contains any body is called abstract methods.
    - Interface in Java is a blueprint that defines what a class must do (methods), not how it does it.
    - Suppose we implement any interface we need to write abstract methods implementation inside the interface in the classes in which we are implementing the interface
    - Implementing interface is nothing but overriding the abstract methods.
    - Suppose we are adding one more abstract method in the interface so classes who implemented that interface will get compilation
      error(need to write implementation of abstract methods) so that is why default and static methods comes in front.
    - diff between the default and static method is that we can override the default method but we cannot override static methods
    - also we can call default methods using the object but for static we call it using the class name or that interface name.
    - also if we have to concrete method we need to use the default keyword in it.
    - Default and static methods introduced to provide backword compatability.
    - Interface methods are public by default, so the implementing class must implement them as public.
Ex. forEach() method added in java.util.Iterable interface as default method in java 1.8v.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2) Lambda Expression:
    - A lambda expression is a short way to write a method without a name.
    - Lambda Expressions introduced in java to enable functional programming(FP means one function can passed as parameter in methods).
    - Lambda is an anonymous function which does not have any name, access modifier and return type also.

    Q. Why lambda has NO name, modifier, or return type?
    - Method name comes from functional interface
    - Access modifier is inherited
    - Return type is inferred by compiler

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

3) Functional Interface:
    - If there is only one abstract method inside the interface then it will be called as functional interface.
    - Also when we write @FI then our compiler will check interface contains only one abstract method or not.
    - A lambda expression needs a functional interface to know what method it is implementing.
    - Below are some predefined functional interfaces.
        Runnable -----> run() method
        Callable -----> call() method
        Comparable ---> compareTo()
    - To represent the interface as Functional Interface we will use @FunctionalInterface Annotation.

    Q: Do we need to implement Runnable or Callable? This is a very common confusion.
    - Runnable and Callable are: predefined functional interfaces
    - provided by Java (java.lang, java.util.concurrent)
    - But they are NOT mandatory.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


